728237f-a.title: Queens: Wyckoff Avenue - Cooper Avenue
728237f-a.text:
Wyckoff Ave., at the S.W. corner of Cooper Ave. (formerly Lawrence
Street); showing the Norman Van Nostrand farmhogse from 1852-1860.
This place was known as ''TRe Little Pink House.'' Norman Van Nostrand
came here from New York City. He settled on forty acres of land and
erected this house thereon in 1852. This house which was demolished in
1910 was also known becsuse the feast church services of the St. Thomas
Episcopal Church (located on Bushwick Ave. and Cooper Street, Nings
County) were held here during the winter of 1871.
1909.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

726375f-c.title: Queens: Cooper Avenue - Wyckoff Avenue
726375f-c.text:
Cooper Ave., at S.W. corner of Wyckoff Ave., showing the home
occupied by John E. Van Nostrand in 1873. This is a set of three
views. No. 3 is on Wyckoff Ave. It was demolished in April 1929.
1909.
Views 2 \& 3: March 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

726376f-a.title: Queens: Cooper Avenue - Wyckoff Avenue
726376f-a.text:
Cooper Ave., at the S.E. corner of Wyckoff Ave., showing a house
in the Cemetery of the Evergreens. The Queens Atlas of 1914 and
1929 show no house on this property. Hoeever, the Queens Atlas of
1909 does show this house at the above location.
May 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
